					<div class="copy">
						<div class='posterousGalleryMainDiv p_embed p_image_embed' data-posterous-file-list='%5B%7B%22large%22%3A%22http%3A%2F%2Fgetfile9.posterous.com%2Fgetfile%2Ffiles.posterous.com%2Fimport-sges%2FvogrpprjpmxuvmexmjybhzBvtfkhFgECgJCfbCivdgBIqntnBHmgnnikyhHn%2Fmedia_httpfarm4static_FEHcf.jpg.scaled1000.jpg%22%2C%22originalWidth%22%3A%22500%22%2C%22largeWidth%22%3A%22500%22%2C%22thumb%22%3A%22http%3A%2F%2Fgetfile0.posterous.com%2Fgetfile%2Ffiles.posterous.com%2Fimport-sges%2FvogrpprjpmxuvmexmjybhzBvtfkhFgECgJCfbCivdgBIqntnBHmgnnikyhHn%2Fmedia_httpfarm4static_FEHcf.jpg.thumb.jpg%22%2C%22originalHeight%22%3A%22375%22%2C%22largeHeight%22%3A%22375%22%2C%22thumbWidth%22%3A%2236%22%2C%22height%22%3A%22375%22%2C%22main%22%3A%22http%3A%2F%2Fgetfile2.posterous.com%2Fgetfile%2Ffiles.posterous.com%2Fimport-sges%2FvogrpprjpmxuvmexmjybhzBvtfkhFgECgJCfbCivdgBIqntnBHmgnnikyhHn%2Fmedia_httpfarm4static_FEHcf.jpg.scaled500.jpg%22%2C%22thumbHeight%22%3A%2236%22%2C%22originalSize%22%3A%22101%22%2C%22original%22%3A%22http%3A%2F%2Fgetfile6.posterous.com%2Fgetfile%2Ffiles.posterous.com%2Fimport-sges%2FvogrpprjpmxuvmexmjybhzBvtfkhFgECgJCfbCivdgBIqntnBHmgnnikyhHn%2Fmedia_httpfarm4static_FEHcf.jpg%22%2C%22width%22%3A%22500%22%7D%5D' data-posterous-image-gallery-initialized='false' data-posterous-image-gallery='true' data-posterous-options='%7B%22zipFile%22%3Anull%2C%22zipFileSize%22%3Anull%2C%22external_url%22%3A%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.flickr.com%2Fphotos%2Fjohn_lam%2F2678358233%2F%22%2C%22showDownload%22%3Atrue%2C%22url_slug%22%3A%22ironruby-at-oscon%22%7D'>
<img alt="Media_httpfarm4static_fehcf" height="375" src="http://getfile2.posterous.com/getfile/files.posterous.com/import-sges/vogrpprjpmxuvmexmjybhzBvtfkhFgECgJCfbCivdgBIqntnBHmgnnikyhHn/media_httpfarm4static_FEHcf.jpg.scaled500.jpg" width="500" />

</div>
<a href="http://en.oreilly.com/oscon2008/public/content/home">OSCON</a> is a happy place for me. It&rsquo;s my third OSCON, and I created good memories at each one. At my first OSCON, I was showing off <a href="http://rubyforge.org/projects/rubyclr/">RubyCLR</a> to the world, and I met some folks from Microsoft who convinced me that it was the right time in my life to go ship something big. At my second OSCON, I was working for The Man, and we announced that were accepting contributions into <a href="http://ironruby.net">IronRuby</a> &ndash; a big change at the time.

Today, we&rsquo;re raising the bar even higher in IronRuby. There are three changes happening today:

1. We&rsquo;re shipping our <a href="http://rubyforge.org/projects/ironruby">first binary release</a>. In this package, we&rsquo;re taking a &ldquo;batteries included&rdquo; approach and shipping the Ruby standard libraries in it. This takes us a big step closer towards &ldquo;IronRuby runs real Ruby programs&rdquo;.

2. We&rsquo;re announcing a new project: <a href="http://github.com/ironruby/ironruby-contrib/tree">ironruby-contrib</a>. It&rsquo;s hosted at <a href="http://github.com">GitHub</a>, an awesome place to do collaborative development. The goal of ironruby-contrib is to provide a place where folks from the community can participate in projects that enhance IronRuby or its underlying platforms. The first project in ironruby-contrib is the Rails plugin that we demonstrated at <a href="http://en.oreilly.com/rails2008/public/content/home">RailsConf</a> this year. It makes it easier for Rails developers to add <a href="http://silverlight.net">Silverlight</a> to their Rails applications, and contains some of our ideas about migrating controller code to the client. <a href="http://blog.jimmy.schementi.com/">Jimmy Schementi</a> is the brains behind the project; see his <a href="http://blog.jimmy.schementi.com/2008/07/browser-meet-ruby-on-rails.html">introductory blog post</a> for more details.

3. We&rsquo;re announcing that we&rsquo;ve submitted our first set of changes to the awesome <a href="http://rubyspec.org">RubySpec</a> project. We&rsquo;ve been <em>talking</em> about contributing to RubySpec for a long time now, but various things kept us from doing so. We&rsquo;ve fixed those things now, which takes us a big step closer towards being an active participant in all things Open Source, and not just the things that we create.
						
					</div>

